First notice that  
  
\quad 1–2v = –(2v–1),  
  
so  
  
\quad \frac{2v+4}{1–2v} = \frac{2v+4}{–(2v–1)} = –\frac{2v+4}{2v–1}.  
  
Hence  
  
\quad \frac{10v}{2v–1} + \frac{2v+4}{1–2v}  
= \frac{10v}{2v–1} – \frac{2v+4}{2v–1}  
= \frac{10v – (2v+4)}{2v–1}  
= \frac{10v –2v –4}{2v–1}  
= \frac{8v –4}{2v–1}  
= \frac{4(2v–1)}{2v–1}  
= 4  
  
(provided 2v–1 ≠ 0, i.e. v ≠ ½).

To combine the three fractions, note that c²–4=(c–2)(c+2), so the common denominator is (c–2)(c+2).  Rewriting each term over that denominator:

1.  c/(c+2)=c(c–2)/[(c–2)(c+2)]  
2.  5/(c–2)=5(c+2)/[(c–2)(c+2)]  
3.  10c/(c²–4)=10c/[(c–2)(c+2)]  

Putting them together:

\[
\frac{c(c-2)}{(c-2)(c+2)}
+\frac{5(c+2)}{(c-2)(c+2)}
-\frac{10c}{(c-2)(c+2)}
=\frac{c^2-2c+5c+10-10c}{(c-2)(c+2)}
=\frac{c^2-7c+10}{(c-2)(c+2)}.
\]

Factor the numerator: c²–7c+10=(c–5)(c–2).  Cancel the (c–2)-factor (noting c≠±2):

\[
\boxed{\frac{c-5}{c+2},\quad c\neq2,\,-2.}
\]
